description.narrative: (Morocco): In Morocco, private sector growth is constrained by a lack of skills (technical and soft) among workers, while university and vocational graduates often struggle to find employment on par with their qualifications. USAID Career Center works to help bridge the gap between the end of education and beginning of employment through two lines of effort: establishing a series of high quality career development centers at public universities and vocational institutions; and embedding work readiness training into the Moroccan tertiary and vocational education systems. USAID will open the remaining sixth physical career center, while ensuring that the model meets host-country expectations to ensure long-term sustainability. Improving youth employability is a strategic goal of Mission Morocco and a wise investment in Morocco's future economic and social stability. Of the total planned funding, $2,500,000 is attributed to the Higher Education earmark.

Objectives for Morocco: The project works to reduce women’s barriers to accessing employment opportunities by designing and delivering work readiness training and career counseling services. It also contributes to changing norms and beliefs in order to encourage both men and women to work in sectors or positions that are not traditionally filled by their gender.
